{
  "answer": "**In Cynewulf's *Andreas*, Latin directly surfaces in the Old English verse as the loan phrase \"Cheruphim et Seraphim\" (lines 719–720), where the biblical names of the highest angelic orders—from Isaiah 6:2–3 in the Vulgate—are embedded verbatim, complete with the Latin connective \"et\".**[^1]\n\nThis occurs as Christ describes paintings on the Jerusalem temple wall depicting heaven's throne room: the \"Cheruphim et Seraphim\" stand before God's face, \"singallice singaþ in wuldre hædrum stefnum heofoncyninges lof\" (\"continually sing with resonant voices the praise of the king of heaven\"), chanting the *Sanctus* (\"Halig is se halga...\"). Theologically, it invokes the celestial hierarchy (per Pseudo-Dionysius, mediated via Latin fathers like Gregory the Great) to affirm Christ's divinity: these supreme angels, fiery throne-bearers who veil their faces in awe, recognize and herald the incarnate God amid skeptical Jewish priests. The raw Latin underscores the poem's patristic pedigree, blending OE heroic idiom with authoritative scriptural/liturical terms to dazzle the audience with heavenly splendor and refute doubters.[^1]: /works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/1/original/#p-a8debb (paragraph containing lines 715–750; exact line from Krapp-Dobbie edition aligns with verse layout).\n\nNo other overt Latin phrases appear in Cynewulf's signed poems (*Elene*, *Juliana*), though calques abound (e.g., *Elene* 89–94 renders the *In hoc signo vinces* vision as \"Mid þys beacne... feond oferswiðesð\"). The corpus lacks deeper syntactic Latinisms beyond such loans/names, as Cynewulf clothes theology in native verse.",
